Taliban insurgents Tuesday ambushed a military-contracted helicopter that made an emergency landing in northwestern Afghanistan, killing three people in a shootout and capturing 16 others who were on board, Afghan officials said.

Col. Michael T. Lawhorn, spokesman for the U.S. support mission in Afghanistan, said the U.S. military had no reports of any Americans on board the helicopter that was attacked.
link_name: Afghan Taliban ambush helicopter after emergency landing; 3 die

status_message:
Turkish fighter jets shot down a Russian warplane Tuesday after it breached the Turkish border, according to media reports.

Russian President Vladimir Putin says the event will have "tragic consequences" for ties between the two countries. Turkey said it shot down the warplane after it ventured into Turkish airspace, but Russia's defense ministry said the aircraft remained within Syria.
link_name: Putin calls Turkey downing warplane 'a stab in back'

DEVELOPING STORY: Turkish jets on Friday shot down an unidentified drone that violated Turkey's airspace at the border with Syria, the military said.

According to a U.S. defense official, the drone was not American, and the U.S. believes it was Russian. The official was not authorized to discuss details of the incident and so spoke on condition of anonymity.

In Moscow, a senior military officer strongly denied that the drone was Russian.
link_name: Turkey says it has shot down unidentified drone at Syrian border

status_message: OUR VIEW: May is National Military Appreciation Month, and for U.S. society at large, it is essential to bear in mind that "acknowledgment" is not the same as understanding — a prerequisite for true appreciation. An equally important prerequisite to appreciation is to avoid misunderstanding. The greatest disservice that can be done to our veterans is to lump them all into a single highly skewed stereotype. No, the first step to truly appreciating the service and sacrifice of America's veterans is to understand that the vast majority served with honor while in uniform and continue to do so in civilian life, as neighbors, co-workers, spouses, parents and members of their communities. Read more here:
link_name: Editorial: Appreciating veterans - the right way

status_message:
IN CASE YOU MISSED IT: Staff Sgt. Richard Faulkner was the only surviving crew member when his bomber was shot down on a mission to Augsburg, Germany, on March 18, 1944. He spent a month eluding the Nazis in occupied France and later declined a Purple Heart because he did not feel it was right to accept the decoration after all his buddies perished. Late last month, at age 89, Faulkner finally received his Purple Heart because he wants to pass it down to his grandchildren.

Help us share this man's story of service and sacrifice.
link_name: After 70 years, WWII gunner finally accepts Purple Heart
